# Mobile-First Design

This app is **mobile-first**. All layout, typography, and UI decisions should assume the default viewport is a phone; larger breakpoints add or adjust, not the other way around.

## Principles

- **Base styles = mobile**: Default (unprefixed) Tailwind classes define the small-screen experience.
- **Progressive enhancement**: Use `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:` to add or change styles for larger viewports only when needed.
- **Touch-friendly**: Prefer tap targets ≥ 44px, spacing that works with thumbs, and avoid hover-only interactions for critical actions.
- **Content priority**: On small screens, show the most important content first; hide or collapse secondary UI behind patterns like tabs, sheets, or “more” actions.

## Tailwind Usage

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — desktop-first (overriding at mobile)
<div className="grid grid-cols-4 gap-4 md:grid-cols-1 md:gap-2">

// ✅ GOOD — mobile-first (base = mobile, then add columns on larger)
<div className="grid grid-cols-1 gap-2 sm:gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — large text by default, shrunk on mobile
<p className="text-lg md:text-sm">

// ✅ GOOD — readable on mobile, optionally larger on desktop
<p className="text-sm sm:text-base">
```

## Checklist for UI Work

- [ ] Default (unprefixed) styles are correct for a narrow viewport (~375px).
- [ ] Breakpoint prefixes only add or refine; they don’t “fix” a desktop-first base.
- [ ] Critical actions are tappable and not hidden behind hover-only behavior on mobile.
